  "pinData": {
    "When Executed by Another Workflow": [
      {
        "json": {
          "Post": "Here's the post:\n\n---\n\n**Most heat-related illness is preventable. That's actually the important part.**\n\nSummer in Northern Virginia is no joke. The humidity alone changes the math on how long a person can safely be outside, and a lot of people underestimate that until something goes wrong.\n\nA few things worth understanding before the hottest weeks hit:\n\n**Hydration works best when it's consistent.** Waiting until you're thirsty means you're already playing catch-up. Small amounts of water throughout the day do more than a large amount all at once.\n\n**Heat exhaustion and heat stroke are different situations.** Heat exhaustion usually involves heavy sweating, weakness, and nausea. Heat stroke is more serious: the sweating often stops, thinking becomes unclear, and body temperature can spike above 103°F. One can be managed carefully at home. The other cannot.\n\n**Children and older adults need extra attention.** They are less reliable at signaling when something feels wrong, and their bodies respond to heat differently than a healthy adult's does.\n\n**Parked cars are dangerous faster than most people expect.** Even on a mild day, interior temperatures rise quickly. There is no errand short enough to make that a safe choice.\n\nWhen you're not sure whether something needs medical attention, Patient First is right here in the shopping center, no appointment necessary.\n\nThe heat is manageable. It just takes a little knowledge.\n\n---"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
